Heart-wrenching numbers are falling daily, but Hubei still has more than 8,000 patients, a quarter of whom are critically ill or even critically ill. Taking them from death is the ultimate battle in this war

This article was adapted from the Southern People's weekly

By Yang Nan, southern people weekly staff writer, Wuhan

He Peiyun, intern reporter for southern people weekly

Editor in chief | Jianping Zhou

In Wuhan, many people thought that the difficulty in treating the critically ill patients with NCP was caused by the shortage of medical resources in the early stage. But there is a growing realization that the root cause of the problem lies in our lack of knowledge about the most serious consequences of the virus.

There is a new coronavirus in human evolution, but the cost of understanding it is a life.

ICU (Intensive Care Unit) is the last pass in medical treatment. It's like a flashlight beam shining into a dark hole: It allows you to see the most dangerous corner of the new crown, with limited visibility, but enough to plunge you into the dark.

This is the ultimate battle for the patient and the ultimate battle for the doctor.

You tried to save him, but you couldn't

Zheng Xia tugged at the Zipper of the protective clothing, but it could not be zipped up. She heard the ward monitor beeping and saw the monitor flashing red. But she can't get in. The Ward's a contaminated area, and her Hazmat suits are always a mess. She can't save anyone.

The ringing of the doorbell pulled Zheng Xia out of this nightmare. Time's up. She's supposed to be working at Golden Pond Hospital.

In Wuhan, many ICU medical care will have nightmares, dream is continuous CPR, keep pressing; is how can not connect, tube always drop; It's an awful lot of people calling themselves names, even though most critically ill people have trouble making a sound. A doctor has whiskey in his room, the smoky, strong-tasting kind, and he often needs it to help him sleep.

Not a good night's sleep, according to more than two dozen ICU doctors interviewed.

Initially with "after entering to beat the virus" mood, Zheng Xia in the new year 30(January 24) that day arrived in Wuhan Jinyintan Hospital. She is the chief physician of ICU of the First Affiliated Hospital of Zhejiang University Medical College and an outstanding doctor of young ICU in China.

Entering the first day of the Golden Pool ICU, Zheng Xia walked into the ward alone. She started with a intubated patient who wasn't sedated, who was Oxygenation, and who was heavily anti-aircraft. "Put her on some sedatives and some pressors, " she told the nurse.

The nurse told her that there was no deep vein injection, only peripheral injection. "then use m-hydroxylamine, " Ms. Zheng said. Before hydroxylamine, the patient's blood pressure fell, Zheng Xia had to use the most basic large-dose fluid to maintain patient blood pressure.

"Are you the doctor on duty? " A nurse suddenly asked her.

"Yes. "

"The patient over there lost his blood pressure and went into shock, " the nurse said.

In another ward, the patient had "acid YTHT" and a Ph of 6.9.

Zheng Xia trotted back and forth between the two wards. Her blood pressure stabilized and there was no effect in rectifying the acid.

"It was almost a crash. The acidosis was so bad that the body was gone in the middle of the night. When I looked back, he had been acidosis for a long time, but I couldn't do so much on my own. You wanted to save him, but you couldn't. "

She didn't have any help. Before her arrival, the ICU was reduced to two undergraduate doctors —— and three on medical leave. The hospital transferred two AIDS doctor support, two people stare and sincerely said: "We will make doctor's orders, but will not see (pneumonia) patients. " Nurses are even more scarce, almost one person when four people. Not to mention that the doctors and nurses of the Golden Pool have lasted more than 20 days, but they are frequently faced with the plight of the patients who can not be treated, or even die in one day.

"None of us who had been seriously ill had ever heard of a gold and silver lake before, and we felt very mysterious, " Sang said, imagining what the lake would look like on the way. It was probably a clean, well-equipped treatment center.

He was deputy director of the Guangzhou Institute of Respiratory Disease Icu physician, Zhong Nanshan Team members, and Zheng Xia went to Han the same day, the two together took over the south seventh floor of the ICU ward.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Photo / interviewees provided

In fact, the wards were so small and dark that they lacked the equipment of a standard ICU in the early stages of an outbreak -- as if there wasn't enough oxygen. This is an infectious disease hospital far away from the urban area of Wuhan. It has the ability to quickly activate the protection mechanism to deal with infectious diseases, but it is not enough by itself to face the influx of critically ill patients.

Wuhan's new pneumonia critically ill continue to turn to the gold and Silver Lake. ICU doctor is the last pass to save the patient's life.

But what if we don't even give them a chance?

Most patients sent to the gold and Silver Lake is the end of the disease process, and even became "half a dead man" just sent to the gold and Silver Lake. Not only in the gold and silver pool ICU, we have heard such a past in many ICU ward in Wuhan: The patient was pressed cardiopulmonary resuscitation; The patient came in cold... All the doctor could do was to resuscitate him for half an hour and issue a death certificate.

"It's not your fault the patient is dying. " Someone tried to Comfort Sang Ling.

"whose fault do you think the shock was? You had several people dead in front of you, and none of them looked comfortable. I've seen a lot of it. I can take it better, but it's still uncomfortable, " Ms. Sang said.

Patients become numbers. The night shift doctor told Sang Ling at the end of his shift that another patient had died last night. Sanling hasn't seen him.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
On February 13, medical staff were busy in the ICU of Wuhan Jinyintan Hospital

Photograph by Chen Zhuo

Sitting in the gold and silver intensive care unit, the team of experts decided to apply for more reinforcements to fight death

Zheng Xia and Sang Ling by the Health Commission medical treatment experts designated to Wuhan. A week before their arrival, three members of the panel, Du Bin, Tong Chaohui and Qiu Haibo, had spent five agonizing days in Wuhan.

They spent their days in three wards of the gold and Silver Lake, two of them makeshift wards. Even the country's best ICU doctors, such as du Bin, Director of internal medicine and ICU at the Peking Union Medical College Hospital, would feel overwhelmed in Wuhan.

"In the first few days, I went to see a patient who had a CO2 reading in the column XXX. It was so undetectable that there were no numbers. I spent the morning by my bed, and by the time I got out of the room at noon, it was over 115."

Finally, but 115 is well above the detection limit.

"I just feel so devastated. You have no idea what you're doing. What is the effect of your doing? " Du said.

In Wuhan in January, you felt "broken" and "powerless, " even as a member of the central guidance team -- a doctor could be one of the most important players in the epidemic.

"At the beginning, there were too many regrets, too many, " said Qiu Haibo, a member of the Expert Group and Deputy Director of the Zhongda Hospital affiliated to Southeast University. "You really feel powerless and helpless. "

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Critically ill doctor Chao Yali shot this scene, Qiu Haibo (right) and du Bin (left) forget to eat lunch, holding a piece of bread, rushed to the next hospital patrol

Photo / interviewees

In addition to the gold and Silver Pool area, the expert group will also visit other hospitals in Wuhan. The wards are full, and outside are hundreds or even thousands of outpatient patients every day. They are stranded in the lobby of the clinic or forced to return home.

"We don't know how many patients are waiting to enter the ICU, and we don't know if these critically ill patients are 'gone' outside the ward, " Qiu said. He received a call for his dying father for a gold and silver lake bed, but no way.

"A lot of patients you can't help. We can't get in without beds, we don't have the equipment, we don't have the equipment, we don't have enough trained staff, and that was a big problem in the early days. I can only say that when I go to see patients on my own, I am determined to do what I can."

Before solving scientific problems, we must first solve the problem of shortage of medical staff and beds.

January 22,2020, at the end of the day in the gold and silver pool rounds, the expert group sitting in the gold and silver pool ICU decided to apply to the National Health Commission to send some experts into the gold and silver pool. At least one ward will have two more specialists in charge of the ward, and three or four more doctors working on it. Zheng Xia and sang Ling were the two named that night. "We bring in the top young doctors in the country, who tend to have strong ideas and are skilled in clinical practice, " Qiu said.

The day before, Tong Chaohui, a member of the Expert Group and Deputy Director of Chaoyang Hospital, had made his first recommendation to his superiors: Open nucleic acid test sites and identify and treat as many patients as possible.

Between January 22 and February 5, the number of new coronavirus nucleic acid test sites in Wuhan expanded from one to 27 in the province, and the number of sentinel hospitals increased from 12 to 28, doubling the number of beds to 8,574. On January 31 and February 9, all the beds in the court district and Guanggu district of Wuhan's most powerful Tongji Hospital were converted to receive new severe cases of pneumonia, with a total of 2,025 patients admitted during the most stressful period.

In 50 days, more than 40,000 medical workers were mobilized across the country to support Hubei, fighting for their lives, including nineteen thousand in intensive care.

A nurse collapsed while carrying an oxygen tank and took only one day off

In interviews in early February, intensive care doctors told us that the situation had improved, and that the total number of deaths in each of the three wards per day was equivalent to that in the previous ward. It was a month later that we learned that the first patients the interviewees had taken over were ultimately not saved.

Many critical care experts in Hubei, who experienced the 2008 Wenchuan County earthquake, generally described the rescue of the new crown disease as more brutal for them. "there wasn't much we could do during the earthquake, " he said. "The pressure was on the rescuers. In addition, the number of casualties brought after the earthquake is decreasing, but this epidemic is more and more critically ill patients,"said a critical doctor.".

Wards are being opened and medical staff are arriving from all over the country.

But by early February, hospitals in Wuhan were running low on oxygen.

Almost all the intensive care units in the city, including Qiu Haibo, carried oxygen tanks in January. More than 100 patients in only four critical care units require hyperbaric oxygen, several times the daily oxygen consumption of the Jinyintan oxygen supply station. Every day at midnight and 7 am, there is also a sudden loss of oxygen. "It can kill you, " one doctor said.

An oxygen tank can only use less than an hour, oxygen delivery master can not come over, the nurses to move their own higher than people oxygen tank. In late January, a nurse in Zheng Xia's ward fainted while carrying oxygen tanks at night. The head nurse insisted that she rest for three days. She only had one day off because she was short-handed.

At Tongji Hospital, the Peking Union Medical College Hospital was the first to take over the ICU ward. On the first night of the February 4th Handover, the ward received 18 patients, even three in a minute.

"For the ICU of Peking Union Medical College, we don't receive 18 patients a day, " said Zhou Xiang, deputy director of the ICU. "In normal work, one or two patients are in danger every day, unlike these 18 patients, who could die at any time. ".

"Your Ward has 30 beds. Why did you only admit 18 patients on the first day? "

"because we only have 18 breathing machines, " Zhou said.

By the next day, Zhou had 32 patients, 28 of whom were intubated. This is the most powerful but the most difficult care measure in routine inhalation therapy. A special trachea is inserted into the patient's trachea, and oxygen is delivered directly to the patient's deep airway through a ventilation device.

"The doctor was in a lot of pain. We did everything we could for all the patients, we did everything we could, but we didn't get out, " Zhou said.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Photo of Zhou Xiang (centre) with colleagues / interviewees

In the North Concord Ward, the median stay of the first serious patients in the ward was 5 days, the shortest was 0 minutes.

By mid-early February, under the efforts of all parties, Wuhan or a new oxygen station, expansion of oxygen tubes, or deployment of breathing machines, and so on, the problem of oxygen supply to hospitals gradually resolved.

The illusion of silence

Qiu Haibo suspected that the machine was broken.

The Monitor showed that the patient had a Oxygenation score of at least 90 on the Oxygenation, with coma possible below 70.

The patient was not comatose, and she was quietly wearing a non-invasive respirator, which emitted low levels of oxygen, not tachypnea, and not a fast heart rate. Except for the constant alarm monitors, everything looks normal.

In 30 years, Qiu Haibo has never seen such a low Oxygenation.

He took off the patient's oximeter and put it on his hand. The Monitor Oxygenation 98. The machine was working. He touched the patient's fingers, no nail Polish, not a cold fingertip, and the subject was fine.

He adjusted the breathing machine and, in conjunction with the prone position, adjusted the patient's Oxygenation to 90. In the meantime, the patient only tells him one kind of feeling: some hold one's breath.

Qiu Haibo this patient performance is not obvious, but the body has been serious hypoxia clinical phenomenon known as "silent hypoxemia. ". At present, there is no definite pathological analysis that can explain the initiation mechanism of silent hypoxemia. Several doctors speculate that the new coronavirus may have attacked the body's compensatory mechanisms. When the body is in a state of Hypoxia, it produces a nerve impulse, and the receptor perceives it to activate a compensatory mechanism, i. e. , an accelerated heart rate or an intense breath, as if trying to obtain more oxygen for the body. Once compensation is compromised, it can be difficult for doctors to make timely treatment decisions.

The doctor was fooled by the illusion of severe hypoxia and steady breathing. In the early stages of treatment, we hear too many cases of patients who can talk and walk but have already developed lung lesions; patients who talk to doctors in the morning and lose them in the afternoon; doctors who have finished rounds and think everything is fine, take off the protective clothing, behind a ECG monitor "straight. ".

"often we see the patient in Hypoxia and have difficulty breathing again, and we intubate. But now the patient's low oxygen performance is very hidden, and it seems to be corrected after inhaling high oxygen, reminding us to intubate common signs are not obvious, treatment will be delayed,"Qiu said.

By the time a person needs to be intubated, he or she is breathing rapidly, often at the end of the process, and they can not withstand a moment of hypoxia before intubation. At seminars on difficult cases at different hospitals, there have been more than five cases of patients who died after taking off their non-invasive breathing and going to the bathroom, and one case of patients who suddenly died after taking off their oxygen masks and eating.

In the fifth edition of the diagnostic and therapeutic protocols for pneumonia in severe and COVID-19 infections, published on February 5, the term "aspiration support" in the treatment of severe and critically ill patients was changed from a general paragraph to a clear four, the second guideline, "high-flow Nasal Cannula oxygen therapy or non-invasive mechanical ventilation, " states that if the condition does not improve or even deteriorate within a short time (1-2 hours) , tracheal intubation and invasive mechanical ventilation should be carried out promptly, the third is "invasive mechanical ventilation" , that is, tracheal intubation.

In fact, as one of the country's leading experts in respiratory crisis, Tong Zhaohui arrived in Wuhan on the third day, in his notebook marked "intubation" and "transfer of respiratory critical care. In late January, he reached a consensus with Qiu Haibo and du Bin that more aggressive treatment was needed and that early intubation was needed. That consensus was written into the fifth edition of the protocol by three experts.

Provided by Tong Chiu Fai / interviewees

Increase the rate of intubation

This is wartime. Orders are given differently. In mid-february, hospitals in Wuhan were instructed to increase the rate of intubation.

"Is this a medical disturbance? "

"At that time, when we talked about increasing the intubation rate, we didn't mean that you had to reach a certain ratio, nor did we mean that every ward should be intubated. Instead, we found that some of the medical staff in the ward didn't realize the harm of delayed intubation and that non-invasive ventilation could cause the spread of droplets. They said that you couldn't intubate, which was not true, " Du said.

In mid-february, intubation was the biggest medical disagreement in the treatment of neocoronary pneumonia. By combining the advice of a number of specialists in both aspiration and critical care, it was discovered that there was general support for the more familiar non-invasive ventilation among the specialists in the specialty of respiratory diseases; Tend to be more assertive and support intubation (invasive ventilation) . At the same time, after intubation, nursing and in vitro life support are more difficult. ICU doctors are more familiar with out-of-body life support than smoking doctors.

Beyond the differences in medical opinion, there are many reasons not to intubate, such as not having a breathing machine, such as medical personnel not familiar with the technology, etc. .

Endotracheal intubation is a high-risk procedure in which patients may spray secretions, blood, or produce droplets or aerosols, increasing the risk of new coronavirus infection. But on the other hand, patients intubated, breathing into a closed circuit, compared to non-invasive breathing machine and high-flow oxygen, will not appear sputum droplets.

You can't force someone to be a hero. This is a potent infectious disease, if not experienced SARS veterans, the first face of it, fear is inevitable.

On the first day of taking over the Intensive Care Unit at Tongji Hospital's Guanggu district, Shanghai Huashan Hospital, the team leader, Li Shengqing, shouted in the corridor, "you have to hurry up and bring me a person. " She dragged a nurse and pushed the patient to calm and relax his muscles to complete the intubation.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Lee shing-ching to / Fan sze-kwong

Li Shengqing, a 29-year veteran of the army, is a smooth talker. Back at the base, she told all the medical staff, "we have the best hospital experts in the country on our team, and the scientific protection is adequate. " "In this case, " she said bluntly, "you're indulging yourself in fear, which is the same kind of self-indulgence as indulging in pleasure. But we're here to heal. "

During that time, one by one, Tong went to the hospital to give a lecture and spent an hour telling the medical staff that, under the current protective conditions, intubation was not too risky, and intubation was better than no intubation.

In interviews, we learned that in mid to late February, at least five directly dispatched experts from the National Health Commission went to different wards to take the lead in intubating.

"How can a Doctor Watch a patient get worse and do something and not use it? If you don't do it, I'll do it. I'll set an example. Fear is a well-known fact. It's normal. But if you keep talking about fear, it's not right,"Du said.

The controversy over intubation and non-intubation largely ended in early March. Li Shengqing described this as a "blood lesson" , she had seen the patient non-invasive oxygen effect is good, oxygen saturation index stable in 92-93, hesitant to re-decide not to intubate. "I was so happy, I took off my suit, and before I got to the doctor's office, they told me there were no beds 15 or 4. It was amazing. "

She was determined to move forward and intubate early. "There's nothing wrong with moving forward, or people die. "

Dr. Chen Zhuo of the Sichuan Provincial People's Hospital performs tracheal intubation on a new critically ill patient with pneumonia in the temporary ICU ward on the 7th floor of Wuhan Red Cross Hospital on Feb. 16

"It's not just the lungs that are attacked, it's the lungs that are attacked first. "

On February 3, southern people weekly published an interview with Zhong Ming, deputy director of the Department of Critical Care Medicine at the Sun Yat-sen Hospital of Fudan University, he is also the National Health Commission, one of the first well-known experts to help the gold and silver lake. In that report, Zhong was the first to describe to the public the sudden acceleration of the late stages of NCP and the attack on multiple organs, which caused widespread concern.

A month later, Zhong Ming tells us that he has re-examined the clinical picture of an inflammatory storm. "What I was really talking about was a theory of mine, " he says. "I saw a slight increase in IL6, which is an important clinical manifestation of the inflammatory response. But then there were more and more patients and I found that the IL6 was elevated, but not by that much."

Simply put, there is an imbalance of inflammatory factors in the patient's body, but not enough to start a storm.

The inference of bell ringing is a shallow step in the process of understanding new coronary pneumonia. "I think if he raises this issue, people will pay attention to the cytokines on the test sheets, " said an Youzhong, director of the Department of Critical Care Medicine at Peking University People's Hospital. It's a good thing they're talking about it. Even if it doesn't turn out to be the case, it's a new understanding of the coronavirus."

It may be difficult for patients to detect the new coronavirus. His body was moving smoothly as usual.

Suddenly, he was forced to run a marathon, the end of one is another, the distance interlocking, can not stop. Oxygen was all around him, and he was gasping for air, taking puffs, but there wasn't enough. The air passed through his throat, but it could never pass through his lungs. His lungs have consolidated, and the Alveoli have been destroyed, like a pig's liver. Then lung fibrosis, like a long-dried Balloon, loses its elasticity and becomes hard and brittle. Any external force can cause it to undergo a paradigm-like deformation, as if it were stretched open and then broken.

His immune system was on life support, his heart and kidneys were under attack, and he didn't even know it. Suddenly he realized that he was not at the end, but at the edge of a cliff. He fell into the sea, sank, and struggled, but he could no longer breathe.

In the end, the cause of his death was COVID-19 pneumonia.

The new coronavirus attacks not only the lungs, but also the immune system, heart muscle and kidneys. It can also cause carbon dioxide retention in patients, leading to acidosis. This is the last two months, clinicians on the new coronavirus awareness.

In the different hospital's difficult case discussion meeting, has appeared more than ten patients sudden cardiac arrest's case. This may be caused either by a temporary lack of oxygen or by the new coronavirus attacking the heart muscle of the patient. Doctors have observed some elevated markers of myocardial damage, but patients do not have typical signs of heart failure.

In Layman's terms, the patient's heart muscle was damaged, but there was no impairment of heart function. Every cell in the heart is injured, but they're just grinding their teeth, and at some point, all the cells just stop working.

Peking Union Medical College Hospital, head of infectious medicine at the University of California, San Diego, points out that the new coronavirus designation probably understates the most serious consequences of the virus, which should be called "new coronavirus infection. ". "It's not just the lungs that get hit, it's the lungs that get hit first, " Li said.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Wuhan Union Hospital, a patient transferred to a general ward, puts his hands together to show his gratitude to his doctor

"It's hard. We're guessing. "

"every doctor's so-called experience in the face of a new disease is taught to us by the patients who have died, " said Jiang Li, director of ICU at Xuanwu Hospital. She is also the National Health Commission, the first well-known experts to help the gold and silver lake, and Zhong Ming the same ward.

As mentioned above, death occurs suddenly in the ICU and is not permitted by the ICU doctor. Their job is to compete with death, and they have done so many times. They want to know exactly what each patient is supposed to do at each stage of the illness, and then hold the patient.

"Most patients can dance in the shelter, some need high-flow oxygen support, and less than 4 percent will become critically ill. ". On the basis of 50,004 confirmed cases in Wuhan (as of 2400 hours on March 16,2020) , 4% means that 2,000 cases have become critically ill. Doctors often do not know the horrors of a new coronavirus until they have seen a critically ill patient.

Zhou Xiang's real fear came when he saw the autopsy results. The autopsy of the first case of a new-crown patient was not completed until February 16 because of the high risk of infectious disease, poor communication with the patient's family and other factors, report released on 28 February. Zhou Xiang learned from a recent anatomical consultation that the patient had "tumor-like growth of Type II alveolar epithelial cells in the Alveolar epithelium, " which means that the alveolar structure of the patient had been destroyed, this structure is the basis for the normal exchange of gas in the lungs.

"We honestly have no way to deal with this tumor-like growth of Type II cells, " Zhou said.

Unfortunately, autopsies present a terminal state, and we still lack a pathological explanation for the progression of the disease. In other words, clinicians are now only aware of the onset and progression of NCP, and have not yet learned to quickly block progress at any point. After several different discussions of difficult cases, we all heard some well-known medical experts sigh in the elevator: "It's too difficult, we are guessing. "

The World Health Organization (WHO) released a report on the outbreak on March 1, saying that the death rate of patients with severe cases of new pneumonia was more than 50 percent. According to the report of the epidemic situation of Wuhan Health Commission, the mortality rate of the whole hospital was between 9.38% and 12.36% in February, and the mortality rate of ICU was more than 60% in several serious disease areas in Wuhan except the Guanggu Hospital area of Tongji Hospital.

In the interview, Sang said several times that he was "not having fun, " a Cantonese term for feeling uncomfortable. He was a somewhat spirited doctor, and the cases he took to the conference were often for one reason: everything he could, there were signs of improvement, and why suddenly there was no one there?

"I really don't know why people are gone, " Sang said repeatedly. "I can only describe why the disease is so difficult, but I don't know why... "

A doctor in Peking Union Medical College burst into tears during an internal meeting, saying that he felt useless and unable to save anyone; a doctor who assisted the Golden Pool experienced the death of four patients in one night, for days on end, I kept telling people what happened that night. And in mid-february, Zhong Ming said to US wearily, "the past experience does not work, I may have done wrong. "

Doctors and nurses are doing their best, but the human process of recognizing a virulent infectious disease costs one life at a time.

Threshold advance

From early February, experts are constantly being urged to move forward. What Jiang Li would like to do most is to go around all the normal wards once a day and pick out the patients who look like they are about to have problems and have a chance to get into the ICU to be taken care of.

"In the disaster science of Earthquake Emergency Management, for example, doctors like us do not go to the first line of the earthquake, the first line is to screen the wounded, triage the wounded, and then grade the evacuees, " said Jiang.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Provided by Jiang LITU / interviewees

In the second edition of the protocol, issued on 18 January, the National Health and Human Services Commission classified patients as suspected, confirmed, critically ill and critically ill, while in the fifth edition, issued on 5 February, it changed to light, ordinary, heavy and critically ill.

"heavy-duty and critical-duty are a hierarchy of emergency management. Their demand for medical resources is higher, " Qiu explained. Among them, the critically ill patients, is the conventional clinical severe patients.

By mid-february, the National Health Commission explicitly asked the various hospitals to move forward, which became the critical diagnosis of the serious disease treatment. "We urge clinicians to move forward to the threshold and grasp the opportunity to save patients' lives, use the invasive suction machine as early as possible to restore patients' Oxygenation and reduce the mortality rate, " Jiao Yahui, deputy director of the Medical Administration and Hospital Bureau of the National Health and Health Commission, said on Feb. 15.

"The critical care approach is to get in early, but also to look at the light ones. If you transfer someone with mild illness to a hospital, you have to make an early transfer. If it's too heavy, it won't work there. The National Health and Health Commission later asked us to make a special referral principle and procedure,"Tong said.

"early statistics from Wuhan headquarters showed that 130 or 140 people were transferred to hospitals and died, indicating that one was seriously ill and the second was late, " a person close to the health commission told us.

But the level advance is not only early intubation, but also all-round level advance. At the symposium on difficult cases, several doctors pointed out that the new coronary pneumonia is an acute disease, can not wait until the index fell to respond, must be early intervention.

Call on the nineteen thousand ICU nurses in Wuhan to work not only in the ICU -- there are about 400 ICU beds in Wuhan. More ICU care, such as the intensive care teams at Zhongshan Hospital in Shanghai and the People's Hospital affiliated with Peking University, are now in intensive care units that have been transformed from ordinary wards. ICU doctors and nurses are often more sensitive to changes in patients'conditions, "To push the ICU doctor in is to observe the patient carefully. Not only can ICU doctors give full play to their experience and ability in various life support techniques, but they can also evaluate and judge patients well before doing it,"said Luo Zhe, deputy director of the Department of Critical Care at Sun Yat-sen Hospital affiliated to Fudan University.

Since February 22, the first sustained decline in severe cases of new pneumonia has been seen, with a drop of 1,908 cases in three days.

Chen Zhuo waits to be discharged from the Hospital of the Wuhan Red Cross on March 6,2010

Whac-a-mole

It's like whac-a-mole. One comes up, one goes down. Critical care can only do symptomatic treatment, where not to save where.

HAVE PHLEGM ON SPUTUM SPUTUM SPUTUM ASPIRATION, combined with antibiotics, high blood pressure, bad oxygenation can go to adjust the machine or prone position ventilation.

Prone ventilation, a means of improving oxygenation in acute respiratory distress, has worked in some patients, but in almost all. This is in late January Qiu Haibo and their three expert group members in the gold and silver pool to explore the law. They tried continuous prone ventilation, which improved oxygenation in most patients, when the oxygen supply could not be improved and the effect of adjusting the suction machine was not obvious. "continuous 12-hour prone ventilation" was later included in the fifth edition of the protocol.

On March 13, the World Health Organization issued an updated "interim guideline for the clinical management of severe acute respiratory tract infection suspected of COVID-192019" in its treatment advice for critically ill patients, the first three were associated with invasive ventilation, and the fourth was recommended for 12-16 hours per day in the prone position.

Critically ill patients are not only recovered from the new coronavirus, but are also guarded by ICU staff. They monitor every change in the patient, and once they reach the edge of the cliff, the doctor holds the patient as long as he can, and maybe some of them do.

Neopneumonia causes acute respiratory distress, which is treated primarily with restricted fluids. But on the other hand, many patients will cause shock due to co-infection, shock requires fluid resuscitation. ICU doctors often face this dilemma. "The lesser of two evils, " said the bell.

In an adequately equipped ICU, the patient is loaded up with monitoring equipment. The ICU nurse is at the patient's side, as if Django would even move to a bench and adjust the treatment plan according to the indication and the patient's clinical performance.

But the ICU, which has a pool of gold and silver, can initially perform only ecg monitoring, Oxygenation monitoring and noninvasive blood pressure monitoring. Over the past 50 days, the pool has gradually increased the invasive pressure monitoring, Central venous pressure, and end gas carbon dioxide module -- the bell tolled to the Monitor Module, for early management of Carbon Dioxide retention in patients.

The gophers were monitored, and when they appeared, the doctors tried to beat them down, using almost every means available to sustain life. In the Intensive Care Unit of Tongji Hospital, a patient has four machines at his bedside: ECMO, CRRT  , a suction machine, and an infusion pump. He was filled with tubes, one of which led to a thick tube on the CRRT  , about the size of a mineral water bottle. The patient's blood travels a winding path, filtering out the inflammatory mediators and returning to the body.

These are the heavy weapons in medical treatment, with the current medical means to pull a person's life.

But all this can only sustain the patient's life, the decisive factor in recovery is the patient's ability to heal. So the use of ECMO is controversial: Once a patient's heart and lungs become irreversibly damaged and unable to heal, there is no solution, even if it can sustain life.

"The most painful part of the disease is that there is no etiological treatment so far, only supportive treatment, " Zhou said.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Cai Hui, a nurse, comforts a crying baby with COVID-19 pneumonia at the Wuhan Children's Hospital

ICU——“I Care U”

If there is any selfishness in coming to Wuhan, Huang Xiaobo's selfishness is to be a pure doctor.

He was director of the ICU at the Sichuan Provincial People's Hospital and arrived in Wuhan on January 25 with the first medical team from Sichuan Province to take over the Red Cross Hospital -- Foshan -- where the first medical teams were sent to the hospital where the outbreak was most severe. After the Sichuan medical team spent 10 days rebuilding the hospital destroyed by the new coronavirus, Huang's main task was to treat the critically ill, southern people weekly reported earlier.

"For us to be doctors, being doctors is an ideal state. We only need to think about our patients, " Huang said. In Wuhan, doctors do not have to deal with human entanglements: This person is my superior, how do I talk, this person is my subordinate, how do I say. With the financial support of the state, doctors don't have to worry about patients not getting the best care because they don't have enough money to pay for it, nor do they have to be afraid of the doctor patient relationship.

Huang Xiaobo explained ICU as "I Care U" : I take Care of you carefully. It's a rare moment when a patient is completely dependent on a health care provider. The patient would say to the nurse, nurse, I'm very hungry, I want to eat, nurse, peel fruit for him. There were also patients who offered to help because the nurse in the suit blushed under her breath. One nurse said she hadn't felt the value of her profession for a long time, but she still loved it.

The only time Zheng Xia shed a tear was when she was intubating a patient. She said, "when you're better, I'll pull it out, and you can go home. ".

"what's your name, doctor? " The patient asked. "I want to remember you. Thank you. "

Zheng Xia suddenly began to shed tears, and her goggles were all burnt. "I don't know how long he has left after I insert this tube, but he still has me to thank, " Ms. Zheng said.

Because endotracheal intubation can increase the patient's pain and risk of infection, doctors often struggle to persuade family members to consent to intubation. But this time, patients and families are more likely to understand a doctor's decision. In Zheng Xia's ward, a grandmother, after agreeing to be intubated, wrote a suicide note on a piece of paper: I can't get through this. How will the house be divided? How will the money be divided.

Grandma didn't make it, and the family agreed to donate the body for the autopsy.

Even if some patients are unlikely to get better, doctors want to hold them. There are many reasons to hold someone up, such as wanting him to be clean and comfortable and to leave with dignity.

Jiang Lito's oldest patient is Wu Nai (not her real name) , who is in her sixties. She intubated Wu, and two weeks later, the prolonged intubation resulted in a buildup of dirt in her mouth. Jiang Li chose to do for her tracheotomy, "let her go before more or less clean some. "

In the case of new crown pneumonia, the deceased patient was placed in an isolation ward with no family members. He may have paramedics with him, but he can't see their faces. They were all wrapped up, except for one pair of eyes that peeked out from behind their goggles. Throughout February, it was common for doctors and nurses to call the families of the dead, but they could not make it to Florida, where they were also quarantined.

"stalemate" is the most common term used by ICU doctors since March. One of the patients with the longest bell standoff had been intubated for more than a month, and he was reluctant to give it up. Zheng Xia in the hands of a patient has woken up, she passed the most dangerous sedation "off-limits" , with suction machine cooperation, efforts to breathe. As she wheeled her to CT, she wrote two lines for the nurses: Please slow down, I want to see the sights along the way.

"She is a tough person with a strong will to survive, " Ms. Zheng said.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Yang Li, head nurse of Wuhan Red Cross Hospital, sorts through the belongings of a deceased patient with new pneumonia in the temporary ICU ward office on the 7th floor of Wuhan Red Cross Hospital, Feb. 25,2010. "when the epidemic is over, they will try to return the relics to their relatives, " she said. "They must still have the family's most precious memories in their cell phones. " Chen Zhuo

Cover the rear

"What does this outbreak mean for the ICU doctors at China's best hospitals? " We asked Zhou.

"No doctor wants to fail. Maybe I'll be struggling with this disease later, and we still hope to have a solution, " he replied.

Wang Zhen, a psychologist in Wuhan and deputy director of the Shanghai Mental Health Center, told us that some medical workers have appeared in the post-traumatic stress disorder. Some doctors unconsciously avoid the January experience, and when asked, they seem to remember nothing. Some nurses appear "flashback" , patients died before the scene of rescue, always appear suddenly in the eyes.

"She remembers very clearly that the patient was talking for a few minutes and then suddenly she couldn't. Then she felt like she was watching a movie and she could see other people working on the patient, and she was actually involved, but she had no memory of her actions. "

The ICU is often used as a staging ward. Unable to cure the ward, patients will be transferred to the strong medical capacity of the ICU, so that in an internal meeting, deputy director Liu Jihong hair fire: "Do not turn to the ICU again! You are the ICU, on-site Rescue! "

In some cases, elderly patients with mild cases of NCP but other serious illnesses who have been returned by major hospitals are sent to the ICU of district hospitals. In the ICU of a district hospital, 11 patients, all over the age of 70, had negative new crown nucleic acid tests, but other diseases of their own made life-sustaining difficult.

"A large number of patients died within a short period of time, and we all directly or indirectly witnessed the tragedy of a family, which hit US harder than ever, " Zhong said.

In Wuhan, the battle to treat patients with new pneumonia is drawing to a close. Since late February, the number of severe cases of NCP in Wuhan has decreased continuously, from 9,628 to 2,695 on March 16.

Now, we can sometimes see the cherry trees stopped under the photo of the medical staff, the aid of Hubei's field medical staff are also returning to their hometown. By the end of March, all 46 designated hospitals in Wuhan will resume their normal medical system, and Jinyintan Hospital, Lung Hospital and Raytheon Mountain will be the last to receive new patients with pneumonia.

"We have to cut our losses. We come first and go last, " said Jiang Li, who has worked for 54 consecutive days at Jinyin Tan.
